## Review finding from certified-app-v2-5g6

## Problem
In `src/app/api/auth/login/route.ts`, when the handle-mode authorization fails and the fallback (prepending `https://`) also fails, the route throws a generic error message instead of the original error:

```typescript
} catch {
  if (!input.startsWith("http") && !input.startsWith("did")) {
    url = await client.authorize("https://" + input, { ... })
    // ↑ if this also throws, it propagates with its own message (good)
  } else {
    throw new Error("Failed to authorize with handle")
    // ↑ this discards the original error from client.authorize(input)
  }
}
```

When `input` starts with `http` or `did` and `client.authorize()` fails, the original error (which may contain useful diagnostic info like "Handle not found" or "PDS unreachable") is discarded and replaced with the generic "Failed to authorize with handle".

## Fix
Preserve and re-throw the original error:

```typescript
let firstError: unknown
try {
  url = await client.authorize(input, { scope: "..." })
} catch (err) {
  firstError = err
  if (!input.startsWith("http") && !input.startsWith("did")) {
    url = await client.authorize("https://" + input, { scope: "..." })
  } else {
    throw err  // re-throw original error
  }
}
```

## Files
- `src/app/api/auth/login/route.ts` (handle mode catch block, lines ~29-37)

## Review finding from certified-app-v2-5g6

## Problem
In `src/lib/atproto/profile.ts`, the `getProfile` function was migrated from Agent-based calls to `fetch()`. The new code correctly checks `res.status === 400 || res.status === 404` before throwing. However, the old catch block that checked for Agent-style `RecordNotFound` errors was left in place:

```typescript
} catch (error) {
  // Handle record not found - return null instead of throwing
  if (
    (error as { status?: number })?.status === 400 ||           // ← dead: fetch errors don't have .status
    (error as { message?: string })?.message?.includes("RecordNotFound") ||  // ← dead: only if fetch() itself throws
    (error as { error?: string })?.error === "RecordNotFound"   // ← dead: fetch errors don't have .error
  ) {
    return null;
  }
  throw error;
}
```

These checks can never match for `fetch()`-based errors (which are `TypeError` for network failures or `Error` with a message string). The only errors that reach the catch block are network-level failures, which should propagate as errors, not silently return null.

## Fix
Remove the dead RecordNotFound checks from the catch block. The catch block should only re-throw:

```typescript
} catch (error) {
  throw error;
}
```

Or remove the try/catch entirely since the `if (!res.ok)` check handles the 400/404 case.

## Files
- `src/lib/atproto/profile.ts` (getProfile catch block, lines ~39-48)

## Files
- src/lib/auth/session.ts (modify)

## What to do
In the `getSessionDid` function, replace the string comparison of the HMAC signature with `crypto.timingSafeEqual`:

```typescript
// BEFORE (around line 44):
if (providedSignature !== expectedSignature) return null

// AFTER:
import { timingSafeEqual } from "crypto"  // add to existing crypto import

const providedBuf = Buffer.from(providedSignature, "hex")
const expectedBuf = Buffer.from(expectedSignature, "hex")
if (providedBuf.length !== expectedBuf.length || !timingSafeEqual(providedBuf, expectedBuf)) {
  return null
}
```

The length check before `timingSafeEqual` is required because `timingSafeEqual` throws if buffers have different lengths.

## Do not
- Change the HMAC algorithm (keep SHA-256)
- Change the cookie format
- Modify any other files

## Files
- src/app/api/xrpc/[...method]/route.ts (modify — POST handler)

## What to do
In the POST handler, after restoring the OAuth session and getting the DID, validate that write operations target the authenticated users own repo.

Add validation after the session restore block (around line 95):

```typescript
const did = await getSessionDid()
if (!did) return NextResponse.json({ error: "Not authenticated" }, { status: 401 })

// ... restore session, create agent ...

// For methods that accept a repo parameter, validate it matches the authenticated user
const REPO_METHODS = ["com.atproto.repo.putRecord", "com.atproto.repo.deleteRecord"]

if (REPO_METHODS.includes(methodName)) {
  const body = await request.json()
  if (body.repo && body.repo !== did) {
    return NextResponse.json({ error: "Forbidden: cannot write to another users repo" }, { status: 403 })
  }
  // Pass body to the switch case (avoid double-parsing)
}
```

**Important**: Since `request.json()` can only be called once, you need to restructure the POST handler to parse the body once at the top and pass it to each case. Refactor:

```typescript
export async function POST(request: NextRequest, { params }: ...) {
  // ... auth check, session restore ...

  // Parse body once (except for uploadBlob which uses arrayBuffer)
  let body: Record<string, unknown> | null = null
  if (methodName !== "com.atproto.repo.uploadBlob") {
    body = await request.json()
  }

  // Validate repo on write methods
  if (body && ["com.atproto.repo.putRecord", "com.atproto.repo.deleteRecord"].includes(methodName)) {
    if (body.repo && body.repo !== did) {
      return NextResponse.json({ error: "Forbidden: cannot write to another users repo" }, { status: 403 })
    }
  }

  switch (methodName) {
    case "com.atproto.repo.putRecord":
      const result = await agent.com.atproto.repo.putRecord(body as any)
      // ...
  }
}
```

## Do not
- Add validation to GET methods (reads are fine — the PDS controls access)
- Block updateHandle or resetPassword (these dont have a repo field)
- Change the response format
- Modify the GET handler

