## What to do

### MemoryStateStore — Add periodic sweep
Add a `setInterval` in the constructor to sweep expired entries every 60 seconds:

```typescript
export class MemoryStateStore {
  private store = new Map<string, { value: NodeSavedState; expiresAt: number }>()
  private readonly ttlMs: number
  private cleanupInterval: ReturnType<typeof setInterval>

  constructor(ttlMs: number = 600_000) {
    this.ttlMs = ttlMs
    // Sweep expired entries every 60 seconds
    this.cleanupInterval = setInterval(() => this.sweep(), 60_000)
    // Dont block process exit
    if (this.cleanupInterval.unref) this.cleanupInterval.unref()
  }

  private sweep(): void {
    const now = Date.now()
    for (const [key, entry] of this.store) {
      if (now >= entry.expiresAt) {
        this.store.delete(key)
      }
    }
  }

  // ... existing set/get/del methods unchanged
}
```

### Session rotation — Invalidate old session on login
In `src/lib/auth/session.ts`, modify `createSession` to delete any existing session for the same DID before creating a new one:

```typescript
export async function createSession(did: string): Promise<void> {
  // Invalidate any existing session for this DID (session rotation)
  for (const [existingSessionId, existingDid] of sessionToDid.entries()) {
    if (existingDid === did) {
      sessionToDid.delete(existingSessionId)
    }
  }

  // ... rest of existing createSession logic (generate ID, sign, set cookie)
}
```

This ensures that when a user logs in again, their old session cookie becomes invalid.

## Do not
- Change the MemorySessionStore (it has no TTL by design — the OAuth client manages lifecycle)
- Add cleanup to the sessionToDid Map (it is cleaned up via deleteSession and the new rotation logic)
- Change the cookie format or HMAC signing

